511–Male":"1511–Deceased","1440–Male":"1440–Deceased","1440":"1440","1560":"1560","1460":"1460","1482":"1482","1580":"1580","1437":"1437","1458":"1458","1511":"1511","1510":"1510","1497":"1497","about 1511":"about 1511","5 June 1506":"5 June 1506","1495":"1495","1572":"1572","about 1508":"about 1508","1524":"1524","1523":"1523","1500":"1500","1520":"1520","1465":"1465","1540":"1540","1508":"1508","1605":"1605","1506":"1506","1505":"1505","Sweden":"Sweden","Grangärde, Ludvika, Dalarna, Sweden":"Grangärde, Ludvika, Dalarna, Sweden","Grangärde, Dalarna, Sweden":"Grangärde, Dalarna, Sweden","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mattsson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Anders, Erik, Matts, Nils, Bjorn, Gunvor, Per, Sten, Thor, Thorvald, Torvald.","Swedish: patronymic from the personal name <i>Matts</i>, a short form of <i>Matthias</i> or <i>Mattheus</i> (see   Matthew  ). Compare   Matson   and   Mattson  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mattson","meanings":["Americanized form (and a rare Swedish variant) of Swedish   Mattsson  .","Americanized form of Danish and Norwegian   Mattsen   and   Madsen  , cognates of 1.","English (mainly Yorkshire and Derbyshire): variant of   Matson  ."]},{"name":"Matthew","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the Middle English personal name <i>Ma(t)thew</i>, a vernacular form of the Greek New Testament name <i>Matthias</i>, <i>Matthaios</i>, which is ultimately from the Hebrew personal name <i>Matityahu</i> ‘gift of God’. This was taken into Latin as <i>Mat(t)hias</i> and <i>Matthaeus</i> respectively, the former being used for the twelfth apostle (who replaced Judas Iscariot) and the latter for the author of the first Gospel. In many European languages this distinction is reflected in different name forms. The commonest vernacular forms of the personal name, including English <i>Matthew</i>, Old French <i>Matheu</i>, Spanish <i>Mateo</i>, Italian <i>Matteo</i>, Portuguese <i>Mateus</i>, Catalan and Occitan <i>Mateu</i> are generally derived from the form <i>Matthaeus</i>. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, including German   Matthias  , Greek   Mathias   and <b>Mattheos</b>, Assyrian/Chaldean   Matti  , Czech <b>Matěj</b>, Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian   Matej  . The name <i>Matthew</i> is also found among Christians in southern India (compare   Mathai  ), but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US. Compare   Mathew  , see also   Matthews  ."]}]},{"name":"Arvid","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old Norse personal name from <i>arn</i> ‘eagle’ + <i>viðr</i> ‘wood, tree’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1357051,"age":35,"year":"1495","julianDay":2267098,"description":"Russians forces invade Sweden.","jurisdictionLevel":3},{"id":1702078,"age":35,"year":"1495","toYear":"1497","julianDay":2267098,"title":"The Russo-Swedish War","description":"While in an alliance with Grand Prince Ivan III of Moscow, King Hans of Denmark and Norway invaded Sweden and was declared King of Sweden.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russo-Swedish_War_(1495%E2%80%931497)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Swedish War","jurisdictionLevel":3},{"id":1702079,"age":60,"year":"1520","julianDay":2276228,"title":"The Stockholm Bloodbath","description":"A mass execution of Swedish nobles by Danish king Christian II is known as the Stockholm Bloodbath. Christian II invaded Sweden in 1519 and took hold of Stockholm in September 1520. Over 80 nobles were executed for heresy on November 8 and 9. The outrage from the executions led to the Swedish removal of support of the Kalmar Union.","url":"https://www.britannica.com/event/Stockholm-Bloodbath","urlTitle":"Britannica - Stockholm Bloodbath","jurisdictionLevel":3},{"id":1702080,"age":63,"year":"1523","julianDay":2277324,"title":"Swedish War of Liberation","description":"The Swedish War of Liberation was a civil war led by nobleman Gustav Vasa. As Christian II heard of the rebellion, he confronted Vasa's men, who won the battle at Brunbacks Ferry. Christian II was defeated by the Swedes in Stockholm and a truce was agreed upon. Vasa was given as a hostage as a show of good faith until the treaty was signed. The Danish King did not keep his word and Vasa was held as a prisoner for two years until his escape. A bounty was placed on Vasa's head. Vasa worked to inspire many to join his cause and lived under disguise until the Danes surrendered in 1525.","url":"https://www.sweden.org.za/swedish-monarchy-gustav-vasa.html","urlTitle":"Sweden.org - Swedish Monarchy Gustav Vasa","jurisdictionLevel":3},{"id":1702082,"age":64,"year":"1524","julianDay":2277689,"title":"Treaty of Malmo","description":"The Treaty of Malmo was signed on September 1, 1524, which ended the Swedish War of Liberation and the independence of Sweden was recognized by Denmark and Norway.","jurisdictionLevel":3}],"lifeSummary":"When Arfwid Arvid Mattsson was born in 1460, in Grangärde, Dalarna, Sweden, his father, Måns Jönsson Svinhufvud, was 21 and his mother, Carin Staffansdotter, was 23. He had at least 3 sons and 2 daughters with Britta Iversdotter. He died in 1540, in Grangärde, Ludvika, Dalarna, Sweden, at the age of 80."},"et":{"1460–1540":"1460–1540","1458–Male":"1458–Surnud","1465–Male":"1465–Surnud","1482–1572":"1482–1572","1437–1510":"1437–1510","1500–1560":"1500–1560","1505–1580":"1505–1580","1506–1605":"1506–1605","1508–Female":"1508–Surnud","1511–Male":"1511–Surnud","1440–Male":"1440–Surnud","1440":"1440","1560":"1560","1460":"1460","1482":"1482","1580":"1580","1437":"1437","1458":"1458","1511":"1511","1510":"1510","1497":"1497","about 1511":"umbes 1511","5 June 1506":"5. juuni 1506"